[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/calculus-of-variations] Calculus of variations is concerned with variations of functionals, which are small changes in the functional's value due to small changes in the function that is its argument.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/calculus-of-variations] The **first variation** is defined as the linear part of the change in the functional, and the **second variation** is defined as the quadratic part.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/calculus-of-variations] Using the above definitions, especially the definitions of first variation, second variation, and strongly positive, the following sufficient condition for a minimum of a functional can be stated.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] In mathematics, the **direct method in the calculus of variations** is a general method for constructing a proof of the existence of a minimizer for a given functional, introduced by Stanisław Zaremba and David Hilbert around 1900.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The method relies on methods of functional analysis and topology.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] As well as being used to prove the existence of a solution, direct methods may be used to compute the solution to desired accuracy.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The calculus of variations deals with functionals $J:V\to {\bar {\mathbb {R} }}$ , where V is some function space and ${\bar {\mathbb {R} }}=\mathbb {R} \cup \{\infty \}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The main interest of the subject is to find *minimizers* for such functionals, that is, functions $v\in V$ such that $J(v)\leq J(u)$ for all $u\in V$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The standard tool for obtaining necessary conditions for a function to be a minimizer is the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] But seeking a minimizer amongst functions satisfying these may lead to false conclusions if the existence of a minimizer is not established beforehand.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The functional J must be bounded from below to have a minimizer.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] Show that $(u_{n})$ admits some subsequence $(u_{n_{k}})$ , that converges to a $u_{0}\in V$ with respect to a topology $\tau$ on V .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] Show that J is sequentially lower semi-continuous with respect to the topology $\tau$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] To see that this shows the existence of a minimizer, consider the following characterization of sequentially lower-semicontinuous functions.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The direct method may often be applied with success when the space V is a subset of a separable reflexive Banach space W .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] In this case the sequential Banach–Alaoglu theorem implies that any bounded sequence $(u_{n})$ in V has a subsequence that converges to some $u_{0}$ in W with respect to the weak topology.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] J is weakly sequentially lower semi-continuous, i.e., for any weakly convergent sequence $u_{n}\to u_{0}$ it holds that $\liminf _{n\to \infty }J(u_{n})\geq J(u_{0})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The second part is usually accomplished by showing that J admits some growth condition.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] A functional with this property is sometimes called coercive.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] Showing sequential lower semi-continuity is usually the most difficult part when applying the direct method.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] See below for some theorems for a general class of functionals.
