[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The argument of J is a differentiable function $u:\Omega \to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , and its Jacobian $\nabla u(x)$ is identified with a $mn$ -vector.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] When deriving the Euler–Lagrange equation, the common approach is to assume $\Omega$ has a $C^{2}$ boundary and let the domain of definition for J be $C^{2}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] This space is a Banach space when endowed with the supremum norm, but it is not reflexive.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] When applying the direct method, the functional is usually defined on a Sobolev space $W^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ with $p>1$ , which is a reflexive Banach space.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The derivatives of u in the formula for J must then be taken as weak derivatives.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] Another common function space is $W_{g}^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ which is the affine sub space of $W^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ of functions whose trace is some fixed function g in the image of the trace operator.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] This restriction allows finding minimizers of the functional J that satisfy some desired boundary conditions.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] This is similar to solving the Euler–Lagrange equation with Dirichlet boundary conditions.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] Additionally there are settings in which there are minimizers in $W_{g}^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ but not in $W^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The idea of solving minimization problems while restricting the values on the boundary can be further generalized by looking on function spaces where the trace is fixed only on a part of the boundary, and can be arbitrary on the rest.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The next section presents theorems regarding weak sequential lower semi-continuity of functionals of the above type.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] where $\Omega \subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is open, theorems characterizing functions F for which J is weakly sequentially lower-semicontinuous in $W^{1,p}(\Omega ,\mathbb {R} ^{m})$ with $p\geq 1$ is of great importance.
