[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] However, there are many interesting cases where one cannot assume that F is convex.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] The function F has p -growth for some $p>1$ : There exists a constant C such that for every $y\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ and for almost every $x\in \Omega$ $|F(x,y,A)|\leq C(1+|y|^{p}+|A|^{p})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/direct-method-in-the-calculus-of-variations] , since then quasiconvexity is equivalent to convexity.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In the calculus of variations and classical mechanics, the **Euler–Lagrange equations** are a system of second-order ordinary differential equations whose solutions are stationary points of the given action functional.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The equations were discovered in the 1750s by Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler and Italian mathematician Joseph-Louis Lagrange.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Because a differentiable functional is stationary at its local extrema, the Euler–Lagrange equation is useful for solving optimization problems in which, given some functional, one seeks the function minimizing or maximizing it.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] This is analogous to Fermat's theorem in calculus, stating that at any point where a differentiable function attains a local extremum its derivative is zero.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In Lagrangian mechanics, according to Hamilton's principle of stationary action, the evolution of a physical system is described by the solutions to the Euler equation for the action of the system.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In this context Euler equations are usually called **Lagrange equations**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical mechanics, it is equivalent to Newton's laws of motion; indeed, the Euler–Lagrange equations will produce the same equations as Newton's Laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] This is particularly useful when analyzing systems whose force vectors are particularly complicated.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] It has the advantage that it takes the same form in any system of generalized coordinates, and it is better suited to generalizations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In classical field theory there is an analogous equation to calculate the dynamics of a field.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The Euler–Lagrange equation was developed in the 1750s by Euler and Lagrange in connection with their studies of the tautochrone problem.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] This is the problem of determining a curve on which a weighted particle will fall to a fixed point in a fixed amount of time, independent of the starting point.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Lagrange solved this problem in 1755 and sent the solution to Euler.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Both further developed Lagrange's method and applied it to mechanics, which led to the formulation of Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Their correspondence ultimately led to the calculus of variations, a term coined by Euler himself in 1766.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Let $(X,L)$ be a real dynamical system with n degrees of freedom.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] (For those familiar with differential geometry, X is a smooth manifold, and $L\colon {\mathbb {R} }_{t}\times TX\to {\mathbb {R} },$ where $TX$ is the tangent bundle of X ).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] When we say stationary point, we mean a stationary point of S with respect to any small perturbation in ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] See proofs below for more rigorous detail.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The derivation of the one-dimensional Euler–Lagrange equation is one of the classic proofs in mathematics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] It relies on the fundamental lemma of calculus of variations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] We assume that L is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] A weaker assumption can be used, but the proof becomes more difficult.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] If f extremizes the functional subject to the boundary conditions, then any slight perturbation of f that preserves the boundary values must either increase J (if f is a minimizer) or decrease J (if f is a maximizer).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Let $f+\varepsilon \eta$ be the result of such a perturbation $\varepsilon \eta$ of f , where $\varepsilon$ is small and $\eta$ is a differentiable function satisfying $\eta (a)=\eta (b)=0$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The third line follows from the fact that x does not depend on $\varepsilon$ , i.e. ${\frac {\mathrm {d} x}{\mathrm {d} \varepsilon }}=0$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] Given a functional $J=\int _{a}^{b}L(t,y(t),y'(t))\,\mathrm {d} t$ on $C^{1}([a,b])$ with the boundary conditions $y(a)=A$ and $y(b)=B$ , we proceed by approximating the extremal curve by a polygonal line with n segments and passing to the limit as the number of segments grows arbitrarily large.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The left hand side of the previous equation is the functional derivative $\delta J/\delta y$ of the functional J .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] A necessary condition for a differentiable functional to have an extremum on some function is that its functional derivative at that function vanishes, which is granted by the last equation.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] A standard example is finding the real-valued function *y*(*x*) on the interval [*a*, *b*], such that *y*(*a*) = *c* and *y*(*b*) = *d*, for which the path length along the curve traced by *y* is as short as possible.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] that is, the function must have a constant first derivative, and thus its graph is a straight line.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] In such cases, the coordinate *qk* is called a **cyclic coordinate**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] For example, if we use polar coordinates t, r, θ to describe the planar motion of a particle, and if *L* does not depend on θ, the conjugate momentum is the conserved angular momentum.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] under fixed boundary conditions for the function itself as well as for the first $k-1$ derivatives (i.e. for all $f^{(i)},i\in \{0,...,k-1\}$ ).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] The endpoint values of the highest derivative $f^{(k)}$ remain flexible.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] A multi-dimensional generalization comes from considering a function on n variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/euler-lagrange-equation] When *n* = 2 and functional ${\mathcal {I}}$ is the energy functional, this leads to the soap-film minimal surface problem.
