[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In geometry, a **geodesic** (/ˌdʒiː.əˈdɛsɪk, -oʊ-, -ˈdiːsɪk, -zɪk/) is a curve representing in some sense the locally shortest path (arc) between two points in a surface, or more generally in a Riemannian manifold.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The term also has meaning in any differentiable manifold with a connection.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It is a generalization of the notion of a "straight line".
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The noun *geodesic* and the adjective *geodetic* come from *geodesy*, the science of measuring the size and shape of Earth, though many of the underlying principles can be applied to any ellipsoidal geometry.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In the original sense, a geodesic was the shortest route between two points on the Earth's surface.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] For a spherical Earth, it is a segment of a great circle (see also great-circle distance).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The term has since been generalized to more abstract mathematical spaces; for example, in graph theory, one might consider a geodesic between two vertices/nodes of a graph.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In a Riemannian manifold or submanifold, geodesics are characterised by the property of having vanishing geodesic curvature.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] More generally, in the presence of an affine connection, a geodesic is defined to be a curve whose tangent vectors remain parallel if they are transported along it.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Applying this to the Levi-Civita connection of a Riemannian metric recovers the previous notion.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Geodesics are of particular importance in general relativity.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Timelike geodesics in general relativity describe the motion of free falling test particles.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This has some minor technical problems because there is an infinite-dimensional space of different ways to parameterize the shortest path.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It is simpler to restrict the set of curves to those that are parameterized "with constant speed" 1, meaning that the distance from *f*(*s*) to *f*(*t*) along the curve equals |*s*−*t*|.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Equivalently, a different quantity may be used, termed the energy of the curve; minimizing the energy leads to the same equations for a geodesic (here "constant velocity" is a consequence of minimization).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Intuitively, one can understand this second formulation by noting that an elastic band stretched between two points will contract its width, and in so doing will minimize its energy.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The resulting shape of the band is a geodesic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It is possible that several different curves between two points minimize the distance, as is the case for two diametrically opposite points on a sphere.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In such a case, any of these curves is a geodesic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] A contiguous segment of a geodesic is again a geodesic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In general, geodesics are not the same as "shortest curves" between two points, though the two concepts are closely related.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The difference is that geodesics are only *locally* the shortest distance between points, and are parameterized with "constant speed".
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Going the "long way round" on a great circle between two points on a sphere is a geodesic but not the shortest path between the points.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The map $t\to t^{2}$ from the unit interval on the real number line to itself gives the shortest path between 0 and 1, but is not a geodesic because the velocity of the corresponding motion of a point is not constant.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Geodesics are commonly seen in the study of Riemannian geometry and more generally metric geometry.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In general relativity, geodesics in spacetime describe the motion of point particles under the influence of gravity alone.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In particular, the path taken by a falling rock, an orbiting satellite, or the shape of a planetary orbit are all geodesics in curved spacetime.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] More generally, the topic of sub-Riemannian geometry deals with the paths that objects may take when they are not free, and their movement is constrained in various ways.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This article presents the mathematical formalism involved in defining, finding, and proving the existence of geodesics, in the case of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The article Levi-Civita connection discusses the more general case of a pseudo-Riemannian manifold and geodesic (general relativity) discusses the special case of general relativity in greater detail.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The most familiar examples are the straight lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] On a sphere, the images of geodesics are the great circles.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The shortest path from point *A* to point *B* on a sphere is given by the shorter arc of the great circle passing through *A* and *B*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] If *A* and *B* are antipodal points, then there are *infinitely many* shortest paths between them.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Geodesics on an ellipsoid behave in a more complicated way than on a sphere; in particular, they are not closed in general (see figure).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] A **geodesic triangle** is formed by the geodesics joining each pair out of three points on a given surface.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] On the sphere, the geodesics are great circle arcs, forming a spherical triangle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In metric geometry, a geodesic is a curve which is everywhere locally a distance minimizer.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This generalizes the notion of geodesic for Riemannian manifolds.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] If the last equality is satisfied for all *t*1, *t*2 ∈ *I*, the geodesic is called a **minimizing geodesic** or **shortest path**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In general, a metric space may have no geodesics, except constant curves.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] At the other extreme, any two points in a length metric space are joined by a minimizing sequence of rectifiable paths, although this minimizing sequence need not converge to a geodesic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The metric Hopf-Rinow theorem provides situations where a length space is automatically a geodesic space.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Common examples of geodesic metric spaces that are often not manifolds include metric graphs, (locally compact) metric polyhedral complexes, infinite-dimensional pre-Hilbert spaces, and real trees.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The distance $d(p,q)$ between two points p and q of M is defined as the infimum of the length taken over all continuous, piecewise continuously differentiable curves $\gamma :[a,b]\to M$ such that $\gamma (a)=p$ and $\gamma (b)=q$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In Riemannian geometry, all geodesics are locally distance-minimizing paths, but the converse is not true.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In fact, only paths that are both locally distance minimizing and parameterized proportionately to arc-length are geodesics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] All minima of E are also minima of L , but L is a bigger set since paths that are minima of L can be arbitrarily re-parameterized (without changing their length), while minima of E cannot.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] with equality if and only if $g(\gamma ',\gamma ')$ is equal to a constant a.e.; the path should be travelled at constant speed.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It happens that minimizers of $E(\gamma )$ also minimize $L(\gamma )$ , because they turn out to be affinely parameterized, and the inequality is an equality.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The usefulness of this approach is that the problem of seeking minimizers of E is a more robust variational problem.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Indeed, $E(\gamma )$ is a "convex function" of $\gamma$ , so that within each isotopy class of "reasonable functions", one ought to expect existence, uniqueness, and regularity of minimizers.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In contrast, "minimizers" of the functional $L(\gamma )$ are generally not very regular, because arbitrary reparameterizations are allowed.
