[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This is the **geodesic equation**, discussed below.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Techniques of the classical calculus of variations can be applied to examine the energy functional E .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The critical points of the first variation are precisely the geodesics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In an appropriate sense, zeros of the second variation along a geodesic $\gamma$ arise along Jacobi fields.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Jacobi fields are thus regarded as variations through geodesics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] By applying variational techniques from classical mechanics, one can also regard geodesics as Hamiltonian flows.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] They are solutions of the associated Hamilton equations, with (pseudo-)Riemannian metric taken as Hamiltonian.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] at each point along the curve, where ${\dot {\gamma }}$ is the derivative with respect to t .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] More precisely, in order to define the covariant derivative of ${\dot {\gamma }}$ it is necessary first to extend ${\dot {\gamma }}$ to a continuously differentiable vector field in an open set.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] However, the resulting value of (**1**) is independent of the choice of extension.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] where $\gamma ^{\mu }=x^{\mu }\circ \gamma (t)$ are the coordinates of the curve $\gamma (t)$ and $\Gamma _{\mu \nu }^{\lambda }$ are the Christoffel symbols of the connection $\nabla$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This is an ordinary differential equation for the coordinates.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It has a unique solution, given an initial position and an initial velocity.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Therefore, from the point of view of classical mechanics, geodesics can be thought of as trajectories of free particles in a manifold.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Indeed, the equation $\nabla _{\dot {\gamma }}{\dot {\gamma }}=0$ means that the acceleration vector of the curve has no components in the direction of the surface (and therefore it is perpendicular to the tangent plane of the surface at each point of the curve).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] So, the motion is completely determined by the bending of the surface.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] This is also the idea of general relativity where particles move on geodesics and the bending is caused by gravity.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The *local existence and uniqueness theorem* for geodesics states that geodesics on a smooth manifold with an affine connection exist, and are unique.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The proof of this theorem follows from the theory of ordinary differential equations, by noticing that the geodesic equation is a second-order ODE.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Existence and uniqueness then follow from the Picard–Lindelöf theorem for the solutions of ODEs with prescribed initial conditions. γ depends smoothly on both *p* and *V*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In general, *I* may not be all of **R** as for example for an open disc in **R**2.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Any γ extends to all of ℝ if and only if M is geodesically complete.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Thus, *$G^{t}(V)=\exp(tV)$* is the exponential map of the vector *tV*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] A closed orbit of the geodesic flow corresponds to a closed geodesic on *M*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] On a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold, the geodesic flow is identified with a Hamiltonian flow on the cotangent bundle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The Hamiltonian is then given by the inverse of the (pseudo-)Riemannian metric, evaluated against the canonical one-form.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In particular the flow preserves the (pseudo-)Riemannian metric g , i.e.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] In particular, when *V* is a unit vector, $\gamma _{V}$ remains unit speed throughout, so the geodesic flow is tangent to the unit tangent bundle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Liouville's theorem implies invariance of a kinematic measure on the unit tangent bundle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The geodesic flow defines a family of curves in the tangent bundle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The derivatives of these curves define a vector field on the total space of the tangent bundle, known as the **geodesic spray**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The double tangent bundle can be visualized as the space of simultaneous changes of both the base point and velocity, without committing to any method to transport velocity across base points.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] For any $x\in M,\;v\in T_{x}M$ , the vertical fiber $V_{(x,v)}$ is determined by the projection map $\pi :TM\to M$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] It consists of all ways to change the velocity v while fixing the base point x , and it is essentially a copy of $T_{x}M$ translated from $(x,0)$ to $(x,v)$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The affine connection then selects where $(x,v)$ would land under a change of base point while "fixing" velocity, which spans out the horizontal fiber $H_{(x,v)}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] at each point $x\in M,\;v\in T_{x}M$ , here $d\pi :TTM\to TM$ denotes the pushforward (differential) along the projection $\pi :TM\to M$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Intuitively, $d\pi$ discards the change to velocity and preserves change to base point.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] More generally, the same construction allows one to construct a vector field for any Ehresmann connection on the tangent bundle.
