[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Thus apart from specifying a certain class of embedded curves, the geodesic equation also determines a preferred class of parameterizations on each of the curves.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Accordingly, solutions of (**1**) are called geodesics with **affine parameter**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] An affine connection is *determined by* its family of affinely parameterized geodesics, up to torsion (Spivak 1999, Chapter 6, Addendum I).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The torsion itself does not, in fact, affect the family of geodesics, since the geodesic equation depends only on the symmetric part of the connection.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] is skew-symmetric, then $\nabla$ and ${\bar {\nabla }}$ have the same geodesics, with the same affine parameterizations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Furthermore, there is a unique connection having the same geodesics as $\nabla$ , but with vanishing torsion.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Geodesics without a particular parameterization are described by a projective connection.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] Efficient solvers for the minimal geodesic problem on surfaces have been proposed by Mitchell, Kimmel, Crane, and others.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] A ribbon "test" is a way of finding a geodesic on a physical surface.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] The idea is to fit a bit of paper around a straight line (a ribbon) onto a curved surface as closely as possible without stretching or squishing the ribbon (without changing its internal geometry).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] For example, when a ribbon is wound as a ring around a cone, the ribbon would not lie on the cone's surface but stick out, so that circle is not a geodesic on the cone.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] If the ribbon is adjusted so that all its parts touch the cone's surface, it would give an approximation to a geodesic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/geodesic] While geometric in nature, the idea of a shortest path is so general that it easily finds extensive use in nearly all sciences, and in some other disciplines as well.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In physics, **Hamilton's principle** is William Rowan Hamilton's formulation of the principle of stationary action.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] It states that the dynamics of a physical system are determined by a variational problem for a functional based on a single function, the Lagrangian, which may contain all physical information concerning the system and the forces acting on it.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The variational problem is equivalent to and allows for the derivation of the *differential* equations of motion of the physical system.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Although formulated originally for classical mechanics, Hamilton's principle also applies to classical fields such as the electromagnetic and gravitational fields, and plays an important role in quantum mechanics, quantum field theory and criticality theories.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In other words, any *first-order* perturbation of the true evolution results in (at most) *second-order* changes in ${\mathcal {S}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The action ${\mathcal {S}}$ is a functional, i.e., something that takes as its input a function and returns a single number, a scalar.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] That is, the system takes a path in configuration space for which the action is stationary, with fixed boundary conditions at the beginning and the end of the path.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Although Hamilton's principle can be viewed as a postulate effectively replacing Newton's laws of motion, it can also be derived from Newton's laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Where i is the index of a mass, $\mathbf {F} _{i}$ is applied force (excluding constraint forces), ${\textbf {a}}_{i}$ is acceleration of the mass, and $\delta \mathbf {r} _{i}$ is the virtual displacement of the i -th mass consistent with the constraints.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In Hamilton's principle, we define the variations such that they vanish at the endpoints: $\delta \mathbf {r} _{i}(t_{1})=\delta \mathbf {r} _{i}(t_{2})=0$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] This makes the first term on the right disappear completely.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Looking at the applied force term, if the forces are conservative, they can be derived from a potential energy $V(\mathbf {r} _{1},\mathbf {r} _{2},\dots )$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] This is Hamilton's principle for a non-relativistic system of masses in the absence of an electromagnetic field.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Requiring that the true trajectory **q**(*t*) be a stationary point of the action functional ${\mathcal {S}}$ is equivalent to a set of differential equations for **q**(*t*) (the **Euler–Lagrange equations**), which may be derived as follows.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Hamilton's principle requires that this first-order change $\delta {\mathcal {S}}$ is zero for all possible perturbations **ε**(*t*), i.e., the true path is a stationary point of the action functional ${\mathcal {S}}$ (either a minimum, maximum or saddle point).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] These equations are called the Euler–Lagrange equations for the variational problem.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Trivial examples help to appreciate the use of the action principle via the Euler–Lagrange equations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] A free particle (mass *m* and velocity *v*) in Euclidean space moves in a straight line.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Using the Euler–Lagrange equations, this can be shown in polar coordinates as follows.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Thus the Euler–Lagrange formulation can be used to derive Newton's laws.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] remembering that r is also dependent on time and the product rule is needed to compute the total time derivative ${\textstyle {\frac {d}{dt}}mr^{2}{\dot {\varphi }}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The solution of these two equations is given by $r={\sqrt {(at+b)^{2}+c^{2}}}$ $\varphi =\tan ^{-1}\left({\frac {at+b}{c}}\right)+d$ for a set of constants *a*, *b*, *c*, *d* determined by initial conditions.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Thus, indeed, *the solution is a straight line* given in polar coordinates: *a* is the velocity, *c* is the distance of the closest approach to the origin, and *d* is the angle of motion.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Hamilton's principle is an important variational principle in elastodynamics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] As opposed to a system composed of rigid bodies, deformable bodies have an infinite number of degrees of freedom and occupy continuous regions of space; consequently, the state of the system is described by using continuous functions of space and time.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The extended Hamilton Principle for such bodies is given by $\int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}\left[\delta W_{e}+\delta T-\delta U\right]dt=0$ where T is the kinetic energy, U is the elastic energy, *W*e is the work done by external loads on the body, and *t*1, *t*2 the initial and final times.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] If the system is conservative, the work done by external forces may be derived from a scalar potential V.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In this case, $\delta \int _{t_{1}}^{t_{2}}\left[T-(U+V)\right]dt=0.$ This is called Hamilton's principle and it is invariant under coordinate transformations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Hamilton's principle and Maupertuis' principle are occasionally confused and both have been called the principle of least action.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The **action principle** can be extended to obtain the equations of motion for fields, such as the electromagnetic field or gravity.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The Einstein equation utilizes the *Einstein–Hilbert action* as constrained by a variational principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The path of a body in a gravitational field (i.e. free fall in space time, a so-called geodesic) can be found using the action principle.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In quantum mechanics, the system does not follow a single path whose action is stationary, but the behavior of the system depends on all imaginable paths and the value of their action.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] The action corresponding to the various paths is used to calculate the path integral, that gives the probability amplitudes of the various outcomes.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Although equivalent in classical mechanics with Newton's laws, the action principle is better suited for generalizations and plays an important role in modern physics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Indeed, this principle is one of the great generalizations in physical science.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] In particular, it is fully appreciated and best understood within quantum mechanics.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Richard Feynman's path integral formulation of quantum mechanics is based on a stationary-action principle, using path integrals.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/hamilton-s-principle] Maxwell's equations can be derived as conditions of stationary action.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In mathematics, the **Legendre transformation** (or **Legendre transform**), first introduced by Adrien-Marie Legendre in 1787 when studying the minimal surface problem, is an involutive transformation on real-valued functions that are convex on a real variable.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Specifically, if a real-valued multivariable function is convex on one of its independent real variables, then the Legendre transform with respect to this variable is applicable to the function.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In physical problems, the Legendre transform is used to convert functions of one quantity (such as position, pressure, or temperature) into functions of the conjugate quantity (momentum, volume, and entropy, respectively).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In this way, it is commonly used in classical mechanics to derive the Hamiltonian formalism out of the Lagrangian formalism (or vice versa) and in thermodynamics to derive the thermodynamic potentials, as well as in the solution of differential equations of several variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For sufficiently smooth functions on the real line, the Legendre transform $f^{*}$ of a function f can be specified, up to an additive constant, by the condition that the functions' first derivatives are inverse functions of each other.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The generalization of the Legendre transformation to affine spaces and non-convex functions is known as the convex conjugate (also called the Legendre–Fenchel transformation), which can be used to construct a function's convex hull.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The function $f^{*}$ is called the convex conjugate function of f .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For historical reasons (rooted in analytic mechanics), the conjugate variable is often denoted p , instead of $x^{*}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If the convex function f is defined on the whole line and is everywhere differentiable, then $f^{*}(p)=\sup _{x\in I}(px-f(x))=\left(px-f(x)\right)|_{x=(f')^{-1}(p)}$ can be interpreted as the negative of the y -intercept of the tangent line to the graph of f that has slope p .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The Legendre transformation is an application of the duality relationship between points and lines.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The functional relationship specified by f can be represented equally well as a set of $(x,y)$ points, or as a set of tangent lines specified by their slope and intercept values.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Therefore, the Legendre transform of f is $f^{*}(p)=p\cdot {\overline {x}}-f({\overline {x}})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Then, suppose that the first derivative $f'$ is invertible and let the inverse be $g=(f')^{-1}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Then for each ${\textstyle p}$ , the point $g(p)$ is the unique critical point ${\textstyle {\overline {x}}}$ of the function $x\mapsto px-f(x)$ (i.e., ${\overline {x}}=g(p)$ ) because $f'(g(p))=p$ and the function's first derivative with respect to x at $g(p)$ is $p-f'(g(p))=0$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In other words, *$(f^{*})'$ and $f'$ are inverses to each other*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] We can also do this transformation for variables $x_{2},\cdots ,x_{n}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] and each of these three expressions has a physical meaning.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] This definition of the Legendre transformation is the one originally introduced by Legendre in his work in 1787, and is still applied by physicists nowadays.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] As shown above, for a convex function $f(x)$ , with $x={\bar {x}}$ maximizing or making $px-f(x)$ bounded at each p to define the Legendre transform $f^{*}(p)=p{\bar {x}}-f({\bar {x}})$ and with $g\equiv (f')^{-1}$ , the following identities hold.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Consider the exponential function $f(x)=e^{x},$ which has the domain $I=\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] To evaluate the supremum, compute the derivative of $x^{*}x-e^{x}$ with respect to x and set equal to zero: ${\frac {d}{dx}}(x^{*}x-e^{x})=x^{*}-e^{x}=0.$ The second derivative $-e^{x}$ is negative everywhere, so the maximal value is achieved at $x=\ln(x^{*})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Let *f*(*x*) = *cx*2 be defined on **R**, where *c* > 0 is a fixed constant.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For *x** fixed, the function of x, *x***x* − *f*(*x*) = *x***x* − *cx*2 has the first derivative *x** − 2*cx* and second derivative −2*c*; there is one stationary point at *x* = *x**/2*c*, which is always a maximum.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The first derivatives of *f*, 2*cx*, and of *f* *, *x**/(2*c*), are inverse functions to each other.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For *x** fixed, *x***x* − *f*(*x*) is continuous on I compact, hence it always takes a finite maximum on it; it follows that the domain of the Legendre transform of f is *I** = **R**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The stationary point at *x* = *x**/2 (found by setting that the first derivative of *x***x* − *f*(*x*) with respect to x equal to zero) is in the domain [2, 3] if and only if 4 ≤ *x** ≤ 6.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The function *f*(*x*) = *cx* is convex, for every x (strict convexity is not required for the Legendre transformation to be well defined).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] One may check involutivity: of course, *x***x* − *f**(*x**) is always bounded as a function of *x**∈{*c*}, hence *I*** = **R**.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] As an example of a convex continuous function that is not everywhere differentiable, consider $f(x)=|x|$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Let $f(x)=\langle x,Ax\rangle +c$ be defined on *X* = **R***n*, where A is a real, positive definite matrix.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Then f is convex, and $\langle p,x\rangle -f(x)=\langle p,x\rangle -\langle x,Ax\rangle -c,$ has gradient *p* − 2*Ax* and Hessian −2*A*, which is negative; hence the stationary point *x* = *A*−1*p*/2 is a maximum.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The Legendre transform is linked to integration by parts, *p dx* = *d*(*px*) − *x dp*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Since the new independent variable of the transform with respect to f is p, the differentials *dx* and *dy* in df devolve to *dp* and *dy* in the differential of the transform, i.e., we build another function with its differential expressed in terms of the new basis *dp* and *dy*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The function −*g*(*p*, *y*) is the Legendre transform of *f*(*x*, *y*), where only the independent variable x has been supplanted by p.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] This is widely used in thermodynamics, as illustrated below.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] A Legendre transform is used in classical mechanics to derive the Hamiltonian formulation from the Lagrangian formulation, and conversely.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For every q fixed, $L(v,q)$ is a convex function of v , while $V(q)$ plays the role of a constant.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In a more general setting, $(v,q)$ are local coordinates on the tangent bundle $T{\mathcal {M}}$ of a manifold ${\mathcal {M}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For each q, $L(v,q)$ is a convex function of the tangent space *Vq*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The Legendre transform gives the Hamiltonian $H(p,q)$ as a function of the coordinates (*p*, *q*) of the cotangent bundle $T^{*}{\mathcal {M}}$ ; the inner product used to define the Legendre transform is inherited from the pertinent canonical symplectic structure.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In this abstract setting, the Legendre transformation corresponds to the tautological one-form.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The strategy behind the use of Legendre transforms in thermodynamics is to shift from a function that depends on a variable to a new (conjugate) function that depends on a new variable, the conjugate of the original one.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The new variable is the partial derivative of the original function with respect to the original variable.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The new function is the difference between the original function and the product of the old and new variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Typically, this transformation is useful because it shifts the dependence of, e.g., the energy from an extensive variable to its conjugate intensive variable, which can often be controlled more easily in a physical experiment.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] (Subscripts are not necessary by the definition of partial derivatives but left here for clarifying variables.) Stipulating some common reference state, by using the (non-standard) Legendre transform of the internal energy U with respect to volume V, the enthalpy H may be obtained as the following.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] To get the (standard) Legendre transform ${\textstyle U^{*}}$ of the internal energy U with respect to volume V, the function ${\textstyle u\left(p,S,V,\{{{N}_{i}}\}\right)=pV-U}$ is defined first, then it shall be maximized or bounded by V.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] To do this, the condition ${\textstyle {\frac {\partial u}{\partial V}}=p-{\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}=0\to p={\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}}$ needs to be satisfied, so ${\textstyle U^{*}={\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}V-U}$ is obtained.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] This approach is justified because U is a linear function with respect to V (so a convex function on V) by the definition of extensive variables.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The non-standard Legendre transform here is obtained by negating the standard version, so ${\textstyle -U^{*}=H=U-{\frac {\partial U}{\partial V}}V=U+PV}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] H is definitely a state function as it is obtained by adding PV (P and V as state variables) to a state function ${\textstyle U=U\left(S,V,\{N_{i}\}\right)}$ , so its differential is an exact differential.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Because of ${\textstyle dH=T\,dS+V\,dP+\sum \mu _{i}\,dN_{i}}$ and the fact that it must be an exact differential, $H=H(S,P,\{N_{i}\})$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The enthalpy is suitable for description of processes in which the pressure is controlled from the surroundings.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] It is likewise possible to shift the dependence of the energy from the extensive variable of entropy, S, to the (often more convenient) intensive variable T, resulting in the Helmholtz and Gibbs free energies.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The Helmholtz free energy is often the most useful thermodynamic potential when temperature and volume are controlled from the surroundings, while the Gibbs free energy is often the most useful when temperature and pressure are controlled from the surroundings.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] As another example from physics, consider a parallel conductive plate capacitor, in which the plates can move relative to one another.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Such a capacitor would allow transfer of the electric energy which is stored in the capacitor into external mechanical work, done by the force acting on the plates.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] One may think of the electric charge as analogous to the "charge" of a gas in a cylinder, with the resulting mechanical force exerted on a piston.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Compute the force on the plates as a function of **x**, the distance which separates them.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] To find the force, compute the potential energy, and then apply the definition of force as the gradient of the potential energy function.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] where the dependence on the area of the plates, the dielectric constant of the insulation material between the plates, and the separation **x** are abstracted away as the capacitance *C*(**x**).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] where ${\textstyle V(Q,\mathbf {x} )=V(\mathbf {x} )}$ as the charge is fixed in this configuration.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] However, instead, suppose that the *voltage* between the plates *V* is maintained constant as the plate moves by connection to a battery, which is a reservoir for electric charges at a constant potential difference.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Then the amount of *charges* ${\textstyle Q}$ *is a variable* instead of the voltage; ${\textstyle Q}$ and ${\textstyle V}$ are the Legendre conjugate to each other.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] This transformation is possible because ${\textstyle U}$ is now a linear function of ${\textstyle Q}$ so is convex on it.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The two conjugate energies ${\textstyle U}$ and ${\textstyle U^{*}}$ happen to stand opposite to each other (their signs are opposite), only because of the linearity of the capacitance—except now *Q* is no longer a constant.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] They reflect the two different pathways of storing energy into the capacitor, resulting in, for instance, the same "pull" between a capacitor's plates.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In large deviations theory, the *rate function* is defined as the Legendre transformation of the logarithm of the moment generating function of a random variable.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] An important application of the rate function is in the calculation of tail probabilities of sums of i.i.d. random variables, in particular in Cramér's theorem.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If $X_{n}$ are i.i.d. random variables, let $S_{n}=X_{1}+\cdots +X_{n}$ be the associated random walk and $M(\xi )$ the moment generating function of $X_{1}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Since the left-hand side is independent of $\xi$ , we may take the infimum of the right-hand side, which leads one to consider the supremum of $\xi a-\Lambda (\xi )$ , i.e., the Legendre transform of $\Lambda$ , evaluated at $x=a$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Legendre transformation arises naturally in microeconomics in the process of finding the *supply* *S*(*P*) of some product given a fixed price *P* on the market knowing the cost function *C*(*Q*), i.e. the cost for the producer to make/mine/etc.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] A simple theory explains the shape of the supply curve based solely on the cost function.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Let us suppose the market price for a one unit of our product is *P*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For a company selling this good, the best strategy is to adjust the production *Q* so that its profit is maximized.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If we consider the maximal profit as a function of price, ${\text{profit}}_{\text{max}}(P)$ , we see that it is the Legendre transform of the cost function $C(Q)$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] For a strictly convex function, the Legendre transformation can be interpreted as a mapping between the graph of the function and the family of tangents of the graph.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The equation of a line with slope p and y -intercept b is given by $y=px+b$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Being the derivative of a strictly convex function, the function $f'$ is strictly monotone and thus injective.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The multidimensional transform can be interpreted as an encoding of the convex hull of the function's epigraph in terms of its supporting hyperplanes.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] This can be seen as consequence of the following two observations.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] On the one hand, the hyperplane tangent to the epigraph of f at some point $(\mathbf {x} ,f(\mathbf {x} ))\in U\times \mathbb {R}$ has normal vector $(\nabla f(\mathbf {x} ),-1)\in \mathbb {R} ^{n+1}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] On the other hand, any closed convex set $C\in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ can be characterized via the set of its supporting hyperplanes by the equations $\mathbf {x} \cdot \mathbf {n} =h_{C}(\mathbf {n} )$ , where $h_{C}(\mathbf {n} )$ is the support function of C .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] But the definition of Legendre transform via the maximization matches precisely that of the support function, that is, $f^{*}(\mathbf {x} )=h_{\operatorname {epi} (f)}(\mathbf {x} ,-1)$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Alternatively, if X is a vector space and *Y* is its dual vector space, then for each point x of *X* and *y* of *Y*, there is a natural identification of the cotangent spaces T**Xx* with *Y* and T**Yy* with *X*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If f is a real differentiable function over *X*, then its exterior derivative, *df*, is a section of the cotangent bundle T**X* and as such, we can construct a map from *X* to *Y*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Similarly, if g is a real differentiable function over *Y*, then *dg* defines a map from *Y* to *X*.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If both maps happen to be inverses of each other, we say we have a Legendre transform.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The notion of the tautological one-form is commonly used in this setting.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] When the function is not differentiable, the Legendre transform can still be extended, and is known as the Legendre-Fenchel transformation.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In this more general setting, a few properties are lost: for example, the Legendre transform is no longer its own inverse (unless there are extra assumptions, like convexity).
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Let ${\textstyle M}$ be a smooth manifold, let E and ${\textstyle \pi :E\to M}$ be a vector bundle on M and its associated bundle projection, respectively.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Let ${\textstyle L:E\to \mathbb {R} }$ be a smooth function.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] As usual, the dual of ${\textstyle E}$ is denoted by ${\textstyle E^{*}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] The fiber of ${\textstyle \pi }$ over ${\textstyle x\in M}$ is denoted ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ , and the restriction of ${\textstyle L}$ to ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ is denoted by ${\textstyle L|_{E_{x}}:E_{x}\to \mathbb {R} }$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Here we use the fact that since ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ is a vector space, ${\textstyle T_{v}(E_{x})}$ can be identified with ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] In other words, ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} L(v)\in E_{x}^{*}}$ is the covector that sends ${\textstyle w\in E_{x}}$ to the directional derivative ${\textstyle \left.{\frac {d}{dt}}\right|_{t=0}L(v+tw)\in \mathbb {R} }$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] To describe the Legendre transformation locally, let ${\textstyle U\subseteq M}$ be a coordinate chart over which ${\textstyle E}$ is trivial.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Picking a trivialization of ${\textstyle E}$ over ${\textstyle U}$ , we obtain charts ${\textstyle E_{U}\cong U\times \mathbb {R} ^{r}}$ and ${\textstyle E_{U}^{*}\cong U\times \mathbb {R} ^{r}}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] If, as in the classical case, the restriction of ${\textstyle L:E\to \mathbb {R} }$ to each fiber ${\textstyle E_{x}}$ is strictly convex and bounded below by a positive definite quadratic form minus a constant, then the Legendre transform ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} L:E\to E^{*}}$ is a diffeomorphism.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Suppose that ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} L}$ is a diffeomorphism and let ${\textstyle H:E^{*}\to \mathbb {R} }$ be the "Hamiltonian" function defined by $H(p)=p\cdot v-L(v),$ where ${\textstyle v=(\mathbf {F} L)^{-1}(p)}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] Using the natural isomorphism ${\textstyle E\cong E^{**}}$ , we may view the Legendre transformation of ${\textstyle H}$ as a map ${\textstyle \mathbf {F} H:E^{*}\to E}$ .
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] It follows that if a function is homogeneous of degree r then its image under the Legendre transformation is a homogeneous function of degree s, where 1/*r* + 1/*s* = 1.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] (Since *f*(*x*) = *xr*/*r*, with *r* > 1, implies *f**(*p*) = *ps*/*s*.) Thus, the only monomial whose degree is invariant under Legendre transform is the quadratic.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/legendre-transformation] A closed convex function f is symmetric with respect to a given set G of orthogonal linear transformations, $f(Ax)=f(x),\;\forall x,\;\forall A\in G$ if and only if *f** is symmetric with respect to G.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/weierstrass-erdmann-condition] The **Weierstrass–Erdmann condition** is a mathematical result from the calculus of variations, which specifies sufficient conditions for broken extremals (that is, an extremal which is constrained to be smooth except at a finite number of "corners").
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/weierstrass-erdmann-condition] The condition allows one to prove that a corner exists along a given extremal.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/weierstrass-erdmann-condition] As a result, there are many applications to differential geometry.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/weierstrass-erdmann-condition] In calculations of the Weierstrass excess function, it is often helpful to find where corners exist along the curves.
[src:calculus-of-variations-deep/weierstrass-erdmann-condition] Similarly, the condition allows for one to find a minimizing curve for a given integral.
